In a message dated 12/12/01 5:19:12 AM Pacific Standard Time,
incynr8(-at-)lawngnome.org writes:

<<
 Would generator bearings be a good bet if my belt wobbles (vibrates
slightly in and out in the same axis of the pulleys), even though it is
tightened to 1/2 deflection. Vibration diminished at engine expansion
warmup, and is negligble at 1250+ rpm...I turned pulley like crazy when
tightening, she's not crooked. I learned that lesson, along with using
ALL the  >>

take the fan belt off.  grab the gen pulley nut- can you wiggle it? up
and
down or side to side.  Reach around the front of the fan housing and
grab
that big 36mm nut holding the fan to the generator and try to wiggle it.

It is not supposed to wiggle, if it does the bearing at the wiggly end
of the
generator is bad.   Usually there is a sort of whine associated with bad

bearings, and if the rear bearing is bad you can see the pulley wobble.
If
you start the engine up w/o belt and the whine is gone, well, that is
where
it was from.  Don't freak, it is okay to run the motor briefly w/o the
belt,
but don't leave it running or drive like that because of lack of
cooling.  If
you have bad bearings it will wear brushes and belts out, and get worse
until
i dunno it explodes or something, so it would need replacement.


